Mysql Dump
http://dba.stackexchange.com/questions/84223/how-to-backup-live-mysql-database
http://aaronbonner.io/post/5662779872/optimising-backups-with-mysql

--opt --compress

make backup faster

mysqldump -u root -p --single-transaction --quick --lock-tables=false --opt --compress --all-databases (or) DATABASE | gzip > /tmp/OUTPUT.sql.gz
 gzip -d OUTPUT.sql.gz

mysqldump -u root -p --single-transaction --quick --lock-tables=false --opt --compress test1 | gzip > /tmp/test1.sql.gz

mysqldump -u root -p --single-transaction --routines --triggers --all-databases > /tmp/backup_db.sql

sudo innobackupex --user=root --password=rootPASSWORD --host localhost /tmp/
sudo innobackupex --apply-log --use-memory=2G /tmp/$TIMESTAMP/
mysqldump --opt <database> | gzip -c | ssh user@wherever 'cat > /tmp/yourfile.sql.gz'
mysqldump -u $MyUSER -h $MyHOST -p$MyPASS $db > filename
tar -cf - /PATH/TO/backup.sql /PATH/TO/FORUMDIR/ | gzip -c > /PATH/TO/backup.tar.gz

mysqldump -u root -h localhost test | gzip -9 > test-db.sql.gz
gzip -d test-db.sql.gz

Restore you data

Now you can copy your SQL dump to your production server and simply restore the data from your MySQL dump file like this:

mysql -u root -p database < database.sql
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
As long as your total InnoDB dataset is relatively small and you would like to shrink ibdata1, you can do the following:

STEP 01: Schedule downtime

STEP 02: mysqldump all databases to /root/MySQLData.sql

mysqldump -uroot -p --all-databases --routines --triggers > /root/MySQLData.sql 

STEP 03: Run SET GLOBAL innodb_fast_shutdown = 0;

STEP 04: Drop all databases except the mysql and information_schema database

STEP 05: service mysql stop

STEP 06: rm -f /var/lib/mysql/ib*

STEP 07: service mysql start (recreates ibdata1, ib_logfile0, ib_logfile1)

STEP 08: Login to mysql

STEP 09: At mysql prompt, run mysql> source /root/MySQLData.sql

That’s it. I have done this many, many times : Howto: Clean a mysql InnoDB storage engine?

From here, you just have to live with the weird growth due to transactions.

Give it a Try !!!

reference
https://www.linode.com/docs/databases/mysql/back-up-your-mysql-databases
